        "assumptions": [
            {
                "id": "A8",
                "text": "Given Da Vinci’s rule, pipe model theory, and uniform specific leaf mass and wood density, the sink for new-leaf growth and construction respiration is approximately uniform along z and z̃.",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 19,
                        "block_id": "p19_L242-249",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "Given Da Vinci’s rule... pipe model theory... assuming a uniform specific leaf mass and wood density, we expect ... leaf growth ... to be approximately spatially uniform..."
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "id": "A9",
                "text": "By similar logic (particularly Da Vinci’s rule), the sink for stem wood growth and construction respiration is approximately uniform along z and z̃.",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 19,
                        "block_id": "p19_L250-252",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "By similar logic, particularly Da Vinci’s rule... define the sink for wood growth and construction respiration as approximately uniform..."
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "id": "A10",
                "text": "Stem maintenance respiration per unit length is proportional to phloem area distribution along the stem.",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 19,
                        "block_id": "p19_eqS1.11",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "S̄_R,S^- ∝ A_p (S.1.11)"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "id": "A11",
                "text": "Allometric power-laws are assumed: stem diameter varies with distance from apex (d_S ∝ z^a) and phloem thickness scales with stem diameter (d_p ∝ d_S^b).",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 19,
                        "block_id": "p19_eqS1.12",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "d_S ∝ z^a (S.1.12)"
                    },
                    {
                        "page": 20,
                        "block_id": "p20_eqS1.15",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "d_p ∝ d_S^b ∝ z^{ab} (S.1.15)"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "id": "A12",
                "text": "Sapwood area conservation across branch order (Da Vinci’s rule) implies total cross-sectional area summed over furcations A_W is uniform with respect to z; therefore N scales as (H/z)^{2a}.",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 19,
                        "block_id": "p19_L266-270",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "apply Da Vinci’s rule... assume that A_W is uniform with respect to z. Thus, the furcation number, N, scales... (S.1.14)"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "id": "A13",
                "text": "Because generally d_S ≫ d_p, total phloem cross-sectional area summed over furcations can be approximated as A_p ∝ N d_S d_p.",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 20,
                        "block_id": "p20_L274-277",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "Given that generally d_S ≫ d_p, the total phloem cross-sectional area... A_p, can be estimated as the product of d_S and d_p... A_p ∝ N d_S d_p (S.1.16)"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "id": "A14",
                "text": "Allocation fractions sum to unity (u_L + u_S + u_R = 1). Reproduction is ignored explicitly, but the aboveground allocation term (1 − u_R) can still represent all aboveground allocation when reproduction is included. Belowground symbionts can be included if u_R and R_R are interpreted as total belowground growth and respiration.",
                "uncertain": false,
                "evidence": [
                    {
                        "page": 20,
                        "block_id": "p20_L286-293",
                        "char_span": null,
                        "snippet": "u_L + u_S + u_R = 1... ignored reproduction... still holds... not considered symbionts; however, if u_R... and if R_R... then this formulation is still valid."
                    }
                ]
            }
